text: Does anyone know if Europe's work life style has been in the last few years? I know before there were longer lunches and less hours... but I heard they've become more "americanized" over the last several years
I could talk to my French neighbors that go back every year if you'd like?
I believe lunches have gotten shorter but I'm not certain
<@U7TL59B3P>
It’s quite different in different countries
Sweden has had a strong, unionised work force for the past hundred years or so.
So in general, we work 40 h per week, breaks are regulated by law, and you get at least 4 weeks of paid vacation per year.
It’s roughly the same in most of the Western European countries - England, France, Germany, Holland, Belgium etc.
Slightly worse in the old eastern block - I wouldn’t want to be a labourer in Poland for example. Or the Ukraine.
Interesting
Many countries are moving towards shorter weeks as well
In the Nordic countries, many companies and governmental organizations are trying out 35 hour weeks
i heard netherlands do 36 hours per week over 4 days or something like that
had one of my employee go work over there for a week
Maybe some some are trying that there too
To me, the Swedish system is obv king :stuck_out_tongue:
Becase of the vastly superior maternity/paternity leave
As an anecdote, for comparison: My wife and I got 460 days of leave to share between us when our daughter was born, which is the standard model (you get more for twins, for example)
My brother, who lives in Holland, got two days, and his wife got four months
I want what you got
Not the paid leave, just someone who loves me
you can have children without that

But I can't speak for all European countries, ofc
